You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with back command and dirty-tracking

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

    public EditProductViewModel()
    {
        BackCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(OnBackAsync);
    }

    async Task OnBackAsync()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return; // user chose to stay
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the system back gesture/button in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom button handles taps, but you also need to intercept the **hardware/swipe back** gesture — otherwise users can bypass the dialog:

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("editproduct", typeof(EditProductPage));
    }

    protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
    {
        base.OnNavigating(args);

        // Only intercept back navigation (Pop) from the edit page
        if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
            && CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
            && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
            && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

            bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                args.Cancel();

            deferral.Complete();
        }
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `GetDeferral()` + `deferral.Complete()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog resolves.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the custom button tap; `OnNavigating` catches the system back gesture/button so both paths are covered.
